Job Description:
Summary of the Intern role
 The Investment Banking Internship provides student(s) with a hands-on introduction to the role of an Analyst. You will work alongside our banking professionals, from Analyst to Managing Director level, and will gain exposure to a variety of advisory and financing transactions and sector types. The Intern is expected to work on multiple projects simultaneously, with primary responsibilities in the research and analysis related to transaction generation and execution.
 Specific responsibilities will vary and may include conducting industry research, building financial models to analyze potential transactions, preparing client presentation materials, and working with banking teams to execute transactions.
 The primary role of the Intern includes, but is not limited to:

Conducting industry research and building out industry databases;
Preparing presentation materials such as PowerPoint slides and summaries for pitch books;
Working with banking teams to execute transactions; and
Performing in-depth quantitative financial analyses.

Qualifications
 Seeking a 3rd year undergraduate student. The Intern candidate should possess outstanding academic records and have demonstrated strong leadership ability through involvement in extracurricular endeavors such as student government, athletics, and cultural and entrepreneurial activities.
 The ideal candidate will possess the following:

Strong quantitative / analytical skills;
Exposure to finance and accounting and / or quantitative modeling;
Experience with financial modeling and analysis preferred;
Superior attention to detail;
Disciplined work ethic;
Excellent verbal and written communication skills;
Ability to effectively manage multiple simultaneous project deadlines;
Proficiency in Excel and PowerPoint;
Ability to work in teams; and
Highly-motivated and energetic.

How to Apply
 Submit your complete application package (resume, cover letter and most recent unofficial transcript), including projected graduation date.
 Inclusiveness and Equal Opportunity 
Stifel Canada is committed to fostering an inclusive, fair, accessible environment, where all employees and customers feel valued, respected and supported. If you require an accommodation for the recruitment process, please let us know and we will work with you to meet your needs.
 About Stifel
 Stifel Canada (https://www.stifel.com/institutional/StifelCanada) is a leading provider of investment banking services, including advisory and underwriting, institutional sales and trading and research services. We offer a full suite of focused debt capital markets, equity capital markets, financial advisory, and investment services, delivering superior advice and execution to a broad range of corporate clients and institutional investors worldwide.
 Stifel Canada has a strong position in the Canadian market, has an international reach and is continuing to grow by adding top talent. The role offers candidates an opportunity to gain valuable, hands-on work experience that is focused on the financial markets. In Canada, we are primarily organized into industry teams focused on specific sectors. These include: Technology, Consumer, Diversified Industries, Life Sciences, Financial Institutions, Metals & Mining, and Energy & Natural Resources. Stifel Canada is offering a unique opportunity to work with a well-seasoned team with an exceptional track record and a large global network of relationships.
 Stifel Canada is a subsidiary of Stifel Financial Corp., a public (NYSE: SF) full-service global investment bank with over 8,500 personnel operating in Canada, the United States and Europe. This includes over 400 investment banking professionals serving the needs of growth companies through specialized expertise and strong relationships within its core industries. As a growth company itself, Stifel’s passion is in bringing the right combination of people, products and services to the table to help our clients grow and excel for the long term.

Dedicated to sustainable development and the environment, Arup is a unique collective of designers, advisors and technical experts working globally. Founded on our core values including excellence, fair and honourable dealings, and fostering a humane environment, we collaborate with our clients and partners using imagination, technology, and expertise to shape a better world.


We strive to build a more sustainable, resilient, and equitable world. From climate action to social equity, we consider the broadest impacts of our work. Sustainable development is at the heart of everything we do, and this purpose shapes our culture and the focus of our leadership. We incorporate environmental and social benefits into our work with communities and clients. Arup offers a broad and deep range of climate and sustainability services, spanning from decarbonizing buildings and electrifying transport to improving climate resilience. You would be joining our multidisciplinary team focusing on technical excellence and innovative solutions that shape a better future for people and the planet.
 Our Toronto office is seeking a Senior Consultant – Environmental Assessment (EA) to play an active role in the continued development of Arup’s Sustainability and Environmental Consulting business. The successful candidate will be working with a creative, innovative, and self-motivated team of engineers and multi-disciplinary colleagues in Toronto, our other Canadian offices, the USA, South America region, and across the world. The role will support projects spanning a variety of sectors (commercial, government, institutional and transportation projects). You will complement our existing Sustainability, Climate and Environmental Consulting team by providing consulting services related to environmental impact assessment, environmental management and environmental compliance.


The role entails developing and leading the environmental services on our projects, managing your own projects, and being supported by the wider team as necessary. The projects will be diverse and exciting ranging from building scale to larger infrastructure such as transit and bridges. This is an opportunity to participate in creating a strong local team in Toronto, with increased exposure and more responsibility early in the role.


 Responsibilities of this specific role will include, but not be limited to the following:

 Lead EA work for various clients and projects; a strong knowledge of one or more EA processes in Canada is necessary; this may include Federal, Comprehensive, or Class (including Transit Project Assessment Process, Municipal or other similar process);


 Oversee both sub-consultants and internal staff in the completion of technical studies to support the EA process including the compilation of technical material to produce study and project reports;


 Possess a strong technical understanding of environmental disciplines within the impact assessment process; this may include natural environment (aquatic, terrestrial, habitat, species at risk, wetlands, sensitive areas), socio-economic (noise and vibration, air quality, transportation and traffic) and cultural heritage (built heritage, archaeology); 


 Incorporate sustainability, emissions reduction and climate resiliency into project work;


 Support clients in planning Indigenous and stakeholder consultation during EA projects including preparing technical content for public meetings and with other interested parties;


 Foster and maintain excellent relationships with sub-consultants, regulators, elected officials, public interest groups, Indigenous communities and other parties involved in our project work;


 Demonstrate superior interpersonal and negotiation skills in working with other entities, and addressing potentially contentious impacts associated with project work;


 Apply extensive experience and understanding of environmental legislation including the Environmental Assessment Act and many other regulatory requirements pertaining to the natural environment, species at risk, water, heritage, and resource management;


 Advance Arup’s internal corporate initiatives and practices regarding sustainability, including climate related objectives, and nature based solutions; promote these externally and apply to projects;


 Understand various procurement and delivery models including Private Public Partnerships and Design-Build;


 Ensure the planning and completion of post EA obligations such as permits and approvals, and compliance with applicable environmental laws and regulations during implementation and construction;


 Maintain and expand current knowledge of environmental best practices, monitor emerging legislation, new technologies, and changes to current environmental approval processes;


 Participate in professional technical committee work, for example: Professional Associations;


 Demonstrate knowledge of the Brownfield Act, environmental site assessment and remediation, risk assessment and excess soil management legislation in Ontario, and/or environmental management;


 Be responsible for project management of multiple projects to ensure successful delivery to meet client objectives – on time and budget;


 Work to develop client relationships, pursuing new business opportunities and have experience developing proposals;


 Contribute to Arup’s research and development activities; and,


 Have a working knowledge of relevant software, including Microsoft Office suite of software.



 Qualifications

 Qualified professionals will have a Bachelors or Master's degree in Environmental Science, Engineering, Planning or a related field, and a proven track record of at least 10-15 years in the Environmental Assessment and Planning industry.


 A professional designation, or eligibility, in Canada such as P.Eng., P.Geo. or a Professional Planning designation would be an asset.


 Have excellent communication skills essential for team-based working, excellent planning and organization skills required for our fast-paced environment, and be highly motivated, proactive, and willing to take on new challenges.


 Be able to manage multiple projects through project planning, resourcing, budgeting, monitoring and successful project delivery.


 The applicant must be fluent in both written and spoken English. French language skills are an asset.



 Benefits that Work - At Arup, we have a comprehensive and valuable benefits program that works for our employees and their families. These are 100% paid for by Arup except for optional life insurance. These benefits provide health and welfare security for you as well as paid time off for rest and renewal. Our Global Profit Share Plan (paid bi-annually) provides an opportunity for you to share in the success of the Firm. As a valued employee of Arup, you can also choose to participate in our GRRSP 5% company match to help you save for your future.


Flexible Working - We believe that flexible arrangements create a more inclusive way of working that supports our diversity and the wellbeing of our people. Options for alternative schedules and the ability to work outside of the office for a portion of your workweek are available.


If you’re excited about working with Arup but your past experience doesn’t quite align with every qualification of this posting, we encourage you to apply. You just might be the right candidate for this or other roles. We are always looking for great talent to join our team.


 Arup is an equal opportunity employer and will consider applications from all qualified individuals. Every job applicant will be treated equally, fairly and with respect regarding race, colour, ancestry, sex, gender identity or expression, sexual orientation, pregnancy, civil status, age (except as provided by law), creed/religion, political convictions, language, ethnic or national origin, disability/handicap, pardoned record of offences, social condition (marital or family status, receipt of social assistance), and any other ground protected by the applicable human rights legislation.


 Arup is committed to improving accessibility for individuals with disabilities and to ensuring that all of our employees have the support and the tools they need to succeed. We have developed policies relating to human rights, accessibility and accommodation, and provide all our employees with training on these matters either during orientation and/or on an ongoing basis.
 If you are contacted by Arup regarding a job opportunity and you feel you need accommodation during the application process, or have a question about our human rights and accessibility accommodation policies, please speak to Human Resources or send an email to americasbenefits@arup.com or call 646-802-3577 to let us know the nature of your request.

